how install chrome on arch

Installing Google Chrome on Arch Linux is a bit different than on Windows or macOS because Chrome isn't in the official Arch repositories. Instead, it’s hosted in the Arch User Repository (AUR).

Since you are using Arch, I'm assuming you're comfortable with the terminal. Here is the most straightforward way to get it done.

Option 1: The Manual Way (No AUR Helper)
If you don't have an AUR helper (like yay or paru) installed yet, follow these steps:

Install prerequisites:
Make sure you have the base development tools and Git installed.
sudo pacman -S --needed base-devel git

Clone the Chrome package:
Navigate to your downloads folder and pull the build files from the AUR.
git clone https://aur.archlinux.org/google-chrome.git

Build and Install:
Enter the directory and run makepkg. The -s flag installs dependencies, and -i installs the package once built.
cd google-chrome
makepkg -si

Option 2: Using an AUR Helper (Recommended)
If you already have yay or paru installed, it’s a single command. This is much easier for future updates.

Using yay:
yay -S google-chrome

Using paru:
paru -S google-chrome

Why isn't it in the official repo?
Arch Linux officially supports Chromium, the open-source base for Chrome. Because Google Chrome contains proprietary code and a different licensing agreement, Arch devs leave it to the community-maintained AUR.

Quick Comparison
Feature	Chromium	Google Chrome
Source	Open Source	Proprietary
Repository	Official (extra)	AUR
Auto-updates	Via pacman	Via AUR helper
Syncing	Limited	Full Google Integration
Pro Tip: If you want a "de-googled" or purely open-source experience without the proprietary tracking bits, you can simply run sudo pacman -S chromium.

