how about brave?

Brave follows the same logic as Chrome on Arch: it isn't in the official repositories, so you'll need to use the AUR.

The most popular version to install is brave-bin. The -bin suffix means it’s a pre-compiled binary—using this will save you from having to compile the entire browser from source, which can take hours and eat up all your RAM.

Option 1: Using an AUR Helper (Fastest)
If you have yay or paru, just run:

Bash
yay -S brave-bin
Option 2: Manual Install
If you don't use an AUR helper, the process is the same as the Chrome install:

Clone the repo:
git clone https://aur.archlinux.org/brave-bin.git

Build and install:
cd brave-bin
makepkg -si

Alternative: Flatpak
If you prefer sandboxed applications or don't want to mess with the AUR, Brave is officially maintained on Flathub.

Install Flatpak (if you haven't):
sudo pacman -S flatpak

Install Brave:
flatpak install flathub com.brave.Browser

Which one should you pick?
Method	Update Style	Performance
AUR (brave-bin)	System-native; updates via AUR helper.	Best; feels like a native app.
Flatpak	Isolated; updates via flatpak update.	Great; slightly larger disk footprint.
AUR (brave)	Compiles from source.	Not recommended unless you have a supercomputer and a lot of time.
One quick heads-up: Users occasionally report that Brave sets itself as the default image viewer on Arch after installation. If your JPEGs start opening in a browser, just right-click one and reset the "Open With" default back to your preferred image viewer.
